<li>Archer's Bane (&quot;accuracy debuff&quot;)</li>
<li>Monk's Bane (&quot;evasion debuff&quot;)</li>
</ul><br />
Why not take a poll to see which of these &quot;Less Useful&quot; poisons rogues would be most willing to give up to get a snare/slow combo poison?  Then you could take the one that is rogues would be willing to give up and just change the effect from whatever it currently is to a some sort of snare/slow combo effect (and perhaps rename the poison if appropriate) while keeping the same recipe.  That might wind up creating the least amount of work for you, while making the EQ rogue community most happy.<br /></div>
		</td>
    <td width="30" align="center" valign="middle"><img src="/forums/images/closeq.gif" width="30" height="30" align="right"></td>
  </tr>
</table>
</div>Theoretically... Fighters bane is supposed to be an equivalent reduction in damage from the NPC.  It is equivalent to the druid spells that reduce attack ability of the NPC.  These spells have been made more useful in recent expansions because the &quot;attack&quot; ability of NPC's was increased.  It should be useful if you have a slower in the party but not a druid to further &quot;cripple&quot; the NPC.<br />
<br />
It is about 90% of the druid ability.<br />
<br />
The slow is about 90% of the Shaman ability.<br />
<br />
Warlords bane then should be the &quot;ideal&quot; if you have both, because each effect is 47% of the appropriate ability, making it about &quot;94%&quot; effective.<br />
<br />
The archers and monks bane work quite differently and instead of crippling the attack of the NPC, make it more vulnerable to take damage.  These should be ideal if you have a slower and a druid (who also snares) in your group.</div>
    <!-- / message -->
    
    
