    <div align="left" id="post_message_478171"><div align="center" style="margin:5px; margin-top:5px; ">
<table width="85%" border="0" align="center" cellpadding="5" cellspacing="0" bgcolor="#333333" class="bbcodeQUOTE">
  
  <tr>
    <td colspan="3" align="center" valign="middle">
	
	<div align="left"><b><div align="left" style="font-size: 12px; color: #999999; font-family: Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif;"><strong>Ngreth Thergn said:</strong></div></b></div></td>
 
	</tr>
  <tr>   
    <td width="30" align="center" valign="middle"><img src="/forums/images/openq.gif" width="30" height="30" ></td>
    <td>
		<div align="left" style="font-size: 12px; color: #999999; font-family: Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif;">Theoretically... Fighters bane is supposed to be an equivalent reduction in damage from the NPC.  It is equivalent to the druid spells that reduce attack ability of the NPC.  These spells have been made more useful in recent expansions because the &quot;attack&quot; ability of NPC's was increased.  It should be useful if you have a slower in the party but not a druid to further &quot;cripple&quot; the NPC.<br />
<br />
It is about 90% of the druid ability.<br />
<br />
The slow is about 90% of the Shaman ability.<br />
<br />
Warlords bane then should be the &quot;ideal&quot; if you have both, because each effect is 47% of the appropriate ability, making it about &quot;94%&quot; effective.<br />
<br />
The archers and monks bane work quite differently and instead of crippling the attack of the NPC, make it more vulnerable to take damage.  These should be ideal if you have a slower and a druid (who also snares) in your group.</div>
		</td>
    <td width="30" align="center" valign="middle"><img src="/forums/images/closeq.gif" width="30" height="30" align="right"></td>
  </tr>
</table>
</div>Not having parsed any of these effects (and not knowing of any parses of them to which I can refer) I can't honestly say how useful they really are for each of the following situations.<br />
<ol style="list-style-type: decimal"><li>soloing</li>
<li>grouping</li>
<li>raiding</li>
</ol>What I do know is that if a mob is slowed it does significantly less damage than it otherwise would, <i><u>especially</u></i> if the mob came into camp with some sort of haste buff.<br />
<br />
I also know that a mob that turns and runs when its health gets low can produce <i><u>very</u></i> unhappy situations for players, which is why snaring is such a critical capability in zones where the mobs are prone to that behavior.<br />
<br />
Those other effects may well be useful, mind you, but if you get slowing and snaring covered then it seems to me that you've got the two most critical effects covered, especially if the rogue is soloing or hunting with a mercenary healer.<br />
<br />
Having said that, I wouldn't normally want to be in a serious hunting group or raid where they were depending upon me and my poisons for <b><u><i>any</i></u></b> of these effects.  In my experience these effects (slows, snares, debuffs and such) tend to generate huge amounts of hate, and as a rogue that is something I generally try to avoid while raiding or grouping because we're not really a tanking class.<br />
<br />
That means that I'm most likely to use them while soloing or hunting alone with my healer mercenary and in that scenario I'm mainly interested in two things:<br />
<ol style="list-style-type: decimal"><li>reducing the amount of damage the mob does to me, and</li>
<li>preventing the mob from running off to get help from 10 or 20 of his friends.</li>
</ol>In a zone where the mobs don't turn and run when they are low on health the second is, of course, not a concern, but in my experience there are some mobs who are prone to that behavior in most zones.<br />
<br />
I'd really like to see what other rogues have to say about all this, of course.  I'd especially like to hear about just how effective these various debuffing poisons are, and whether my perceptions are supported by parsing.</div>
