</div>well those two specific poisons do NOT have low level versions at all, they only exist in the following forms:<br />
ITEM_NUMBER	NAME<br />
44690	Archer's Bane XI<br />
44691	Archer's Bane XII<br />
44692	Archer's Bane XIII<br />
44693	Archer's Bane XIV<br />
44694	Archer's Bane XV<br />
44695	Monk's Bane X<br />
44696	Monk's Bane XI<br />
44697	Monk's Bane XII<br />
44698	Monk's Bane XIII<br />
44699	Monk's Bane XIV<br />
44700	Monk's Bane XV<br />
<br />
There is no I - X of Archer's Bane, and there is not I - XIV of Monk's Bane<br />
(this is the items)<br />
<br />
As for the spells, there are only 3 of each (strike is the proc)<br />
<br />
SPELLINDEX	SPELLNAME<br />
22220	Archer's Bane Poison I<br />
22221	Archer's Bane Poison Strike I<br />
22222	Archer's Bane Poison II<br />
22223	Archer's Bane Poison Strike II<br />
22224	Archer's Bane Poison III<br />
22225	Archer's Bane Poison Strike III<br />
22226	Monk's Bane Poison I<br />
22227	Monk's Bane Poison Strike I<br />
22228	Monk's Bane Poison II<br />
22229	Monk's Bane Poison Strike II<br />
22230	Monk's Bane Poison III<br />
22231	Monk's Bane Poison Strike III<br />
<br />
The three &quot;strikes&quot; ARE different and offer different levels of effectiveness.<br />
<br />
They do work slightly differently than the slow and snare where the &quot;last&quot; one is just spread across the levels.<br />
<br />
Instead, they are used across two versions each.<br />
I.E. 44690 and 44691 use 22220, 44692 and 44693 use 22222, and 44694 uses 22224.  Similarly on the Monk's Bane with its spells.<br />
<br />
The differences in the pairs are the level on the item to help with resists.<br />
<br />
So just like the snare and slow poison that I was mostly talking about... the &quot;extra&quot; versions are just about resists.<br />
<br />
Now in this particular case, it may not matter as much, since the level ranges are closer together, so you will not see as large of a resist disparity, but I still give it for people that want to &quot;optimize&quot;  because one may be 1 in 9 while the other are 1 in 10.</div>
